Use the 'removeattributes(object)'; function. This will remove any properties associated with the given object, including its parent property if it has one. For example, when calling this method on a customer object:

    customer.removeattributes();

Now all of its attributes (such as name, address, phone number) are no longer attached to it. Just make sure you use quotes around any literal values!

Use the 'fontsize(string)'; function. This will adjust the font size for any given string of characters. For example, when calling this method on a label:

    label.fontsize = '14pt';

Now all of its text is displayed at 14 points per inch! Just make sure you use quotes around any literal values!

Use the constructor for your object. The constructor initializes all of its attributes with default values or zeros if not specified otherwise. For example:
    public class Car {
        public int speed; // attribute declared here
        public string color; // another attribute declared here
        ...
    }
    Now, when you create a new Car object like this:
        Car myCar = new Car();
    The constructor will automatically set all of its attributes to their default values or zeros. You can then use these attributes in your code without worrying about initializing them yourself.
